If you want to optimize your query performance on a large dataset, you can add the following
options to your index definition to limit the amount of data that your MongoDB Search query must traverse:**NumPartitions-syntax:**numPartitionsUse the [numPartitions](fts-index-partition) option to configure partitions for your index.
When you partition your index, MongoDB Search automatically distributes the index objects between sub-indexes in an optimal way.```json
{
  "numPartitions": <integer>,
}
```**StoredSource-syntax:**storedSourceUse the [storedSource](fts-stored-source-definition) option to specify fields in the source document that MongoDB Search must store.```json
{
  "storedSource": true | false | {
    "include" | "exclude": [
      "<field-name>",
      ...
    ]
  }
}
```

To define your search criteria, you must apply one or more [operators](fts-operators) or [collectors](fts-collectors)
to your [$search](pipe.$search) or [$searchMeta](pipe.$searchMeta) pipeline stage.MongoDB Search operators allow you to locate and retrieve relevant data from your cluster according to content, format, or data tyoe.
To learn which operators support searches for each [supported](bson-data-types), see the table in the [operators](fts-operators) reference section.
You must specify one or more indexed search fields in the operator's [query path](ref-path) parameter:**Search-equals-operator:**$search**Input:**```json
{
  $search: {
    "<operator-name>"|"<collector-name>": {
      <operator-specification>|<collector-specification>
    }
  }
}
```**Output:**```
[
  {
    _id: <result-document-id>,
    ...
  },
  {
    _id: <result-document-id>,
    ...
  },
  ...
]
```**SearchMeta-equals-operator:**$searchMeta**Input:**```json
{
  $searchMeta: {
    "<operator-name>"|"<collector-name>": {
      <operator-specification>|<collector-specification>
    }
  }
}
```**Output:**```
[
  {
    count: {
      total: <results-count>
    }
  }
]
```> **Tip:** You can combine multiple operators into one operation using the [compound](compound-ref) operator.
> You can also use the [compound](compound-ref) operator's *filter* clause to filter for query output that matches a given clause.

If you want to retrieve metadata from your MongoDB Search query, you can apply one of the following configurations
to choose between the [count](count-ref) or [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref) type of metadata results document:**Count-option:**Count MetadataTo return the total or lower-bounded count of your search results, set the [count](count-ref) option in your aggregation stage.The [$searchMeta](pipe.$searchMeta) stage returns the `count` metadata results, while the [$search](pipe.$search) stage stores the metadata results in the
[$$SEARCH\_META aggregation variable](fts-aggregation-variable) and returns only the search results.
For an example of how to retrieve the `count` metadata results from the `$$SEARCH_META` variable, see [Count Results](count-results).```json
{
  "$search" | "$searchMeta": {
    "<operator-name>": {
      <operator-specifications>
    },
    "count": {
      "type": "lowerBound" | "total",
      "threshold": <number-of-documents> // Optional
    }
  }
}
```**Facet-collector:**Facet MetadataTo run a facet query, which groups results by values or ranges and returns the count for each of these groups,
use the [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref) collector in your aggregation stage.The [$searchMeta](pipe.$searchMeta) stage returns `facet` metadata results, while the [$search](pipe.$search) stage stores the metadata results in the
[$$SEARCH\_META aggregation variable](fts-aggregation-variable) and returns only the search results.
For an example of how to retrieve the `facet` metadata results from the `$$SEARCH_META` variable, see [Facet Results](fts-facet-results).```json
{
  "$search" | "$searchMeta": {
    "facet": {
      "facets": {
        <facet-definitions>
      }
    }
  }
}
```
